                            <decoDesc>
                                <p>Main text in black ink, rubrics in red.</p>
                                <p>35 full-page miniatures and 1 full-page portrait (later addition). The miniatures are always matched with a facing page large foliate initial that opens the relevant chapter. The illuminations are either framed in gold with an outer border in red or blue ink, e.g. <locus from="55v" to="55v" scheme="folios"/>, or surrounded by a painted border in different colours, e.g. <locus from="111v" to="111v" scheme="folios"/>. The dominating colours are blue, red, green, pink and yellow, as well as pink skin tones. Gold is also used frequently. The miniatures are covered by contemporary red cloth curtains.</p>
                                <p>The motifs consist of key scenes associated with the relevant chapter with characters realistically portrayed in contemporary clothing and armour, e.g. <locus from="131v" to="131v" scheme="folios"/>, and backgrounds often featuring castles or other buildings, e.g. <locus from="70v" to="70v" scheme="folios"/>.</p>
                                <decoNote type="images">
                                    <p>The motifs are: Hours of the Virgin: <locus from="55v" to="55v" scheme="folios"/>: the Annunciation; <locus from="70v" to="70v" scheme="folios"/>: Visitation; <locus from="74v" to="74v" scheme="folios"/>: Nativity; <locus from="78v" to="78v" scheme="folios"/>: Adoration of the Magi; <locus from="82v" to="82v" scheme="folios"/>: Presentation in the Temple; <locus from="86v" to="86v" scheme="folios"/>: Christ and the Doctors in the Temple; <locus from="92v" to="92v" scheme="folios"/>: Death of the Virgin; Prayers/Suffrages: <locus from="99r" to="99r" scheme="folios"/>: The Shroud/Face of Christ; <locus from="99v" to="99v" scheme="folios"/>: Christ with instruments of the Passion; <locus from="107r" to="107r" scheme="folios"/>: St Christopher carrying a child; <locus from="108v" to="108v" scheme="folios"/>: St Leonhard; <locus from="109v" to="109v" scheme="folios"/>: St Eustach; <locus from="111v" to="111v" scheme="folios"/>: Crucifixion; <locus from="113v" to="113v" scheme="folios"/>: Mary Magdalen; <locus from="115r" to="115r" scheme="folios"/>: St Barbara; <locus from="117r" to="117r" scheme="folios"/>: St George; <locus from="118r" to="118r" scheme="folios"/>: St Peter; <locus from="119r" to="119r" scheme="folios"/>: St Bartholomew; <locus from="120r" to="120r" scheme="folios"/>: St Matthew; <locus from="121r" to="121r" scheme="folios"/>: St Florian; <locus from="122r" to="122r" scheme="folios"/>: St Sebastian; Hours of the Passion: <locus from="131v" to="131v" scheme="folios"/>: Christ Before Pilate; <locus from="135r" to="135r" scheme="folios"/>: Christ Carrying the Cross; <locus from="138v" to="138v" scheme="folios"/>: The Crucifixion; <locus from="141v" to="141v" scheme="folios"/>: The Deposition; <locus from="145r" to="145r" scheme="folios"/>: The Entombment; <locus from="149r" to="149r" scheme="folios"/>: The Resurrection; Hours of Corpus Christi: <locus from="153v" to="153v" scheme="folios"/>: The Last Supper; <locus from="158v" to="158v" scheme="folios"/>: Counterfeiting the host; <locus from="160v" to="160v" scheme="folios"/>: Mass interrupted; <locus from="173r" to="173r" scheme="folios"/>: The feast of Corpus Christi; <locus from="178v" to="178v" scheme="folios"/>: Reading of the Mass; <locus from="182v" to="182v" scheme="folios"/>: Miracle of the Sacred Bleeding Host of Dijon; <locus from="186r" to="186r" scheme="folios"/>: Last rites/destrucion of the host?; <locus from="189v" to="189v" scheme="folios"/>: Two kneeling angels holding a monstrance; Portrait: <locus from="202r" to="202r" scheme="folios"/>: later portrait of the Habsburg family. In the center Philip I of Castille, and from the left top corner clockwise: Frederick III, Maximilian I, Ferdinand I, and Carl V.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                                <decoNote type="initials">
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="16r" to="186v" scheme="folios"/>: chapters (the hours, or other major sections) are introduced by a foliate initial over 10 lines. The painted initials are made up of vegetative shapes in shades of either blue, green, red, or solid gold. The counter space is filled with a contrasting colour and vine ornaments (sometimes in gold). The initial is placed on a square background, usually of gold, but sometimes painted in another colour, e.g. <locus from="83v" to="83v" scheme="folios"/>. Elements of the initial extend into the margin to form a leaf-/flower-shaped border, e.g. <locus from="83r" to="83r" scheme="folios"/>. <locus from="190r" to="190r" scheme="folios"/>: inhabited inital. Same style as the others but the counter space is filled with an image of a hooded man in profile and the coat of arms of Johann Siebenhirter. The same coat of arms is also present in the margin on <locus from="139r" to="139r" scheme="folios"/>, and <locus from="149v" to="149v" scheme="folios"/>, where it is hanging from foliage. On <locus from="136r" to="136r" scheme="folios"/>, <locus from="142v" to="142v" scheme="folios"/>, and <locus from="173v" to="173v" scheme="folios"/> the coat of arms of the Order of St George are hanging from foliage; on <locus from="145v" to="145v" scheme="folios"/> it is held by a flower-man. <locus from="98v" to="122v" scheme="folios"/>: a smaller version over 4 lines of the foliate initials are used for the indivudal prayers. <locus from="14r" to="200v" scheme="folios"/>: paragraphs are introduced by plain initials over 2-3 lines in alternating blue and red, while capitals in the same style are used for sentences.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                                <decoNote type="edges">
                                    <p>Gilt edges.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                            </decoDesc>
